                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 312.62/64.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to Consul
                            <persName type="to">Hamm</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-05-29">
                            <hi rend="italic">May 29, 1914</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>State to General Carranza that at request of German Embassy, this city,
                    Department has instructed you to ask him to order release to owner, of hardware
                    store in San Pedro de Las Colonias, Coahuila, and ranch twelve or fifteen miles
                    east of city, both belonging to Mrs. Helena Pfeiffer, a German subject, and
                    seized by Constitutionalists, including quantity of wheat and cotton on ranch.
                    Store said to be in charge of Colonel C. Benavides.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Bryan</hi>
                    </signed>.</closer>
            </div>
        </body>
